Problem 3: 3-D Random Walk

Question a :

We represent a random walk with the package plot 3D. In red is the departure point and in blue is the arrival point of the random walk. In this question we use 10000 iterations.

Last coordinates after random walk of 10 000 iterations
x y z iteration
26 -44 26 10000

Question b :

We now do 100 000 iterations. We also modify the tresholds slightly. Ths modification will tweak the directions. Indeed, instead of having the same chance to go up, down, left or right, here there are slightly more chances to go up on the z dimension.

Last coordinates after random walk of 100 000 iterations
x y z iteration
142 -133 -899 1e+05

Bonus:

a = saveGIF({
  par(mar = rep(3, 4))
  n = 10
  tmax = 30
  set.seed(20161013)
  x = rnorm(n)
  y = rnorm(n)
  ani.options(interval = 0.5, nmax = tmax)  
  for (i in 1:tmax) {
    plot(x, y, pch = 21, cex = 4, 
         col = "red", bg = "yellow",
         xlim = c(-10, 10), ylim =  c(-10, 10),
         main = "Simulation of 2D Brownian Motion")
    text(x, y)
    x = x + rnorm(n)
    y = y + rnorm(n)
    }
  }, movie.name = "Brownian2.gif")
## Output at: Brownian2.gif

Problem 4: Portfolio construction

To construct the portfolio we need first to extract the stock data from internet.

We first exctract the SP500 index tickers from wikipedia.

Here are the 6 first extracted tickers. We can notice that there is 504 and not 500. This is becuase there is more thtan 500 companies listed on the sp500.

We then use those tickers to extract stocks price data from Yahoo. For our model only the daily change in percentage is relevant. So we will exctract only those.

The datas after preparation have 7 columns: a pair of tickers, their daily return, their standard deviation and the covariance. The data frame have 124251 which is the expected number if we combine all the possible pairs of tickers following this equation : \[ \frac{n(n-1)}{2}\]

Now to find the expected return and covariance we will use two functions :

\[Portfolio\; expected \;return: \;\;\;\;\;\; \mathbb{E}(R_p)= w\mathbb{E}(R_{i}) + (1-w)\mathbb{E}(R_{j}) \] \[Portfolio \;return \; variance: \;\;\;\;\;\; \sigma^2_p = w^2\sigma^2_i + (1-w)^2\sigma^2_j + 2w(1-w)\sigma_i\sigma_j\rho_{ij} \]

To facilitate calculations the weight will not be continuous but distrtibuted between 0 and 1 in sequence of 0.1.

For the heavy calculation of running the function 11 times over all the 124251rows the package future was used to distribute the calculation amongst different cores.

After anaylsis the portfolio with the lower standard-deviation is composed of the ticker USB and DUK with a weight of 0.4 and 0.6 respectively. The standard deviation of this portfolio is 0.0069% and the daily expected return is 310^{-4}%.

With one milion invested in this portfolio the daily expected return would be 300$.
